EXAMPLE 4: Differential Privacy — GDPR Article 25 (Privacy by Design)
Model: Small CNN | Dataset: CIFAR-10 (5000 samples) | Opacus DP-SGD
======================================================================

Device: CUDA

⚠️  Note: ε=50.0 does NOT constitute strong privacy.
   For GDPR Art.25 compliance, ε ≤ 8 is recommended (ε ≤ 1 is strong).
   This demo uses ε=50.0 for convergence speed on a small dataset.
   Lower ε → more noise → lower accuracy → stronger privacy guarantee.

Training non-DP baseline for honest accuracy comparison…
Non-DP baseline accuracy: 54.8%  (trained identically, no noise)


⚙️  CompliancePrivacyEngine configured with max_epsilon=8.0
   check_epsilon() will raise EpsilonBudgetExceeded if ε > 8.0
   (same hard-stop semantics as FairnessGate.on_epoch_end)

Training for 5 epochs with ε=50.0, δ=1e-05

Epoch  |     Loss |     Acc |        ε | δ
--------------------------------------------

  [EpsilonBudgetExceeded] ε=26.0 > max_epsilon=8.0
  → In production: raise and stop training (same as FairnessGate)
  → Demo continues with enforcement disabled for remaining epochs

  1     |    2.160 |   26.2% |     26.0 | 1e-5  ⚠️  EXCEEDS max=8.0
  2     |    1.896 |   33.0% |     33.6 | 1e-5  within budget
  3     |    1.882 |   36.1% |     39.7 | 1e-5  within budget
  4     |    1.795 |   38.5% |     45.1 | 1e-5  within budget
  5     |    1.763 |   39.9% |     50.0 | 1e-5  within budget

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Final epsilon         : 50.0  (⚠️  vacuous at this level)
  Final accuracy (DP)   : 39.9%
  Baseline accuracy     : 54.8%  (same model, no noise)
  Privacy-accuracy cost : 14.9% accuracy gap for ε=50.0
  max_grad_norm=1.0 means per-sample gradients clipped to L2-norm ≤ 1.0
  → individual contributions bounded → membership inference harder

